As people are using Visual Studio Online in combination with MyGet, we often get the request to help them set things up. We do have <a href="http://docs.myget.org/docs/reference/vso-integration" target="_blank">documentation VSO integration</a>, but the new <a href="http://aka.ms/vsopreview" target="_blank">VSO Build Preview</a> deserves a dedicated blog post. This blog post should guide you through the setup experience and get you going in no time!<div><br></div><h1>Configuring Package Restore</h1><div>One of the first and most easy things to do is to configure NuGet package restore in your solution.</div><div><br></div><div>When creating a MyGet feed, by default, we will configure nuget.org as an upstream package source. What is very convenient is that you can tweak it further so that:</div><div><ul><li>clients querying your MyGet feed also query the upstream nuget.org package source to resolve packages</li><li>the downstream MyGet feed automatically mirrors the packages queried upstream (thus creating a copy of the package on your MyGet feed)</li><li>you don't see the mirrored packages in your MyGet feed, even though they're there and can be restored (the concept of 'unlisting' a package)</li></ul><div>Three simple checkboxes in the package source configuration make the above possible, as shown below:</div></div><div><img src="data:image/png;base64," style="width: 826px;"><br></div><div><br></div><div>Once enabled, you should see the below package source configuration updated to reflect those changes.</div><div><img src="data:image/png;base64," style="width: 826px;"><br></div><div><br></div><div>In the code base, you should ensure you have a nuget.config file in the solution root directory. This is where you can configure NuGet package restore configuration options, including credentials for your private feed. The below snippet is a good sample of what you need there.</div><div><script src="https://gist.github.com/xavierdecoster/09946213abfca795daff.js"></script></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div>Be sure to add the nuget.config file to your version control system to ensure the build server also has it available.</div><div>Also, be sure to check this NuGet docs article on <a href="http://docs.nuget.org/consume/package-restore#omitting-packages-from-source-control" target="_blank">how to ommit packages from source control</a>. Git users can simply <a href="http://docs.nuget.org/consume/package-restore#git" target="_blank">ignore the packages folder</a> in the .gitignore file, TFVC users need to <a href="http://docs.nuget.org/consume/package-restore#tfvc" target="_blank">create an additional nuget.config file</a> in a directory called .nuget (created in the solution root directory). This may change in the future, so be sure to check the docs!</div><div><br></div><div>That's it! You can now locally restore packages in your solution from both MyGet and nuget.org.</div><div>All you need to do in VSO Build Preview is to create a new Build Definition using the default Visual Studio build template and queue a build.&nbsp;</div><div><img src="data:image/png;base64," style="width: 413px;"><br></div><div><br></div><div>If you consume NuGet packages, you should now already see package restore actions in the build log.</div><div><br></div><div><img src="data:image/png;base64," style="width: 826px;"><br></div><div><br></div><h1>Creating NuGet packages</h1><div>For demo purposes, I'm building a simple class library and want to package-n-publish it to MyGet. We highly recommend you first create a .nuspec file for the project you want to package. You can <a href="http://docs.nuget.org/Create/Nuspec-Reference" target="_blank">construct this NuGet package manifest yourself</a>, use <a href="http://npe.codeplex.com" target="_blank">NuGet Package Explorer</a>, or if you have <a href="https://nuget.org/nuget.exe" target="_blank">nuget.exe</a> at your disposal, simply run <span style="font-weight: bold;">nuget spec</span> in the folder where your target project is located.&nbsp;</div><div><br></div><div><span style="font-style: italic;">Note: if you run nuget spec, please ensure you have all required metadata in your AssemblyInfo file to provided the tokenized nuspec file with actual values during packaging.</span></div><div><span style="font-style: italic;"><br></span></div><div>To create the NuGet packages, you'll need to add a PowerShell script build task to the build definition and call into <span style="font-style: italic;">nuget pack</span>.</div><div><br></div><div><span style="background-color: yellow;">// todo: sample</span></div><div><span style="background-color: yellow;">// add NuGet packaging logic to the custom build task?</span></div><div><br></div><h1>Publish NuGet packages to MyGet</h1><div><span style="background-color: yellow;">// todo: preferably based on the custom build task</span></div><div><span style="background-color: yellow;">// otherwise: PoSh it..</span></div><div><br></div>
